the steady collapse of the Larsen B ice shelf. Larsen B is a 35-square mile gigantic drifting section of floating ice that was once attached to the eastern part of the Antarctic Peninsula.

In January of 2002, an enormous rift was seen to have developed in the ice shelf.

In the spring of the same year, the rift grew deeper and wider. By January 3, 2002, the fallout was so obvious that the countries that signed Antarctica's Environment Protocol (the US, the UK, and Canada) were informed that Larsen B was in danger of splintering much sooner than expected. During this time, the main body of Larsen B was already in two pieces separated by about a quarter of a mile. The predominant winds in the area were blowing towards the west and drove the two pieces into even greater solitudes.

This prompted scientists to watch more closely the giant rift’s movement that threatened to break Larsen B in half.

Image Source: palaeoblog.wordpress.com

Scientists were worried that the crack may soon reach the edges of the ice shelf and partially break it. In early March of 2002, scientists saw the rapids heavenward after the piece broke.

Nonetheless, there was still hope for Larsen B because the piece drifted far away with icebergs jostling for position. They thought that the flow of ice toward the Atlantic Ocean would somehow prevent the breaking up of the ice shelf.
